Here he arrives at that point where his most important task, his universal mission, begins. He was not destined as a statesman to change existing condi- tions and introduce a new order of things, but rather selected as the instrument to bring Greek learning home to the Roman genius‚1 and transmit the Greek idea of culture to posterity. No other Roman possessed such familiarity with all branches of Greek art and learning, or made such earnest endeavors to give it a footing in Roman soil.

What he asserted ten years later with reference to his philo- sophical writings—that he wished to prove himself useful to

his writingS, to none more than the three books de Oratore, in which a wealth of most valuable material for training was brought to his people.
